
[1]elision

   ELI'SION, n. s as z. [L. elisio, from elido, to strike off; e and
   loedo.]

   1. In grammar, the cutting off or suppression of a vowel at the end of
   a word, for the sake of sound or measure, when the next word begins
   with a vowel; as, th' embattled plain; th' empyreal sphere.

   2. Division; separation. [Not used.]
